<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Other popular investment options are looking less attractive. The Chinese property market is no longer the sure bet it once seemed. Prices for newly constructed housing fell 1 to 9 percent in recent months in all 70 mainland cities tracked by the national government, according to <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/19/business/international/in-china-housing-market-pressure-to-sell-hesitation-to-buy.html">data released this month</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And people also appear to be moving money into the stock market from so-called wealth management products, like Yuâe Bao, a hugely popular money market fund controlled by a financial services company affiliated with Alibaba, the e-commerce giant.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yuâe Bao, introduced in June 2013, is already one of the worldâs largest money market funds. But the annual return has fallen to about 4 percent, from nearly 7 percent in January.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âFrom September, I started moving my money, little by little, from wealth management products and Yuâe Bao into the stock market,â said Chen Haowen, 26, an information technology professional in the southern city of Shenzhen.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the most recent quarter, the fundâs assets under management fell for the first time, declining to about 535 billion renminbi at the end of September. Thatâs down from 574 billion renminbi at the end of June.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But as Mr. Chen and others are discovering, Chinaâs stock markets can be much more volatile than money market funds.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThis is the first time I invested in stocks,â Mr. Chen said, adding that he uses social media to track analysis of the markets and for stock recommendations.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI sold some stocks before and made some money, but now, over all, I am losing money,â he said. âI am still learning.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Neil Gough reported from Hong Kong, and Cao Li from Beijing.</em></p>
